          <span slot="en">Modern games are inherently concurrent — <b>render thread</b>, <b>physics thread</b>, <b>audio thread</b>, <b>AI thread</b> run in parallel. C++11 brought concurrency to the standard library (<code>&lt;thread&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;mutex&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;atomic&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;future&gt;</code>); C++20 added <b>coroutines</b> and <code>std::jthread</code>. Mastering multithreading is essential for high-performance game engines — but fraught with pitfalls: data races, deadlocks, false sharing. Click below to watch the producer-consumer sequence diagram.</span>
